{"id":"1107.2401","submitter":"Rahul Kannan","authors":"Rahul Kannan, Andrea V. Macci\\`o, Anna Pasquali, Benjamin P. Moster\n  and Fabian Walter","title":"Interaction between dark matter sub-halos & galactic gaseous disk","comments":"Accepted for publication in The Astrophysical Journal","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/0004-637X/746/1/10","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.CO astro-ph.GA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We investigate the idea that the interaction of Dark Matter (DM) sub-halos\nwith the gaseous disk of galaxies can be the origin for the observed holes and\nshells found in their neutral hydrogen (HI) distributions. We use high\nresolution hydrodynamic simulations to show that pure DM sub-halos impacting a\ngalactic disk are not able to produce holes; on the contrary, they result in\nhigh density regions in the disk. However, sub-halos containing a small amount\nof gas (a few percent of the total DM mass of the sub-halo) are able to\ndisplace the gas in the disk and form holes and shells. The size and lifetime\nof these holes depend on the sub-halo gas mass, density and impact velocity. A\nDM sub-halo of mass $10^8$ $M_{\\odot}$ and a gas mass fraction of $\\sim 3$%, is\nable to create a kpc scale hole, with a lifetime similar to those observed in\nnearby galaxies. We also register an increase in the star formation rate at the\nrim of the hole, again in agreement with observations. Even though the\nproperties off these simulated structures resemble those found in observations\nwe find that the number of predicted holes (based on mass and orbital\ndistributions of DM halos derived from cosmological N-body simulations) falls\nshort compared to the observations. Only a handful of holes are produced per\nGiga year. This leads us to conclude that DM halo impact is not the major\nchannel through which these holes are formed.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 12 Jul 2011 20:00:02 GMT"},{"vers