{"id":"1107.2575","submitter":"Ivo Petras","authors":"Dominik Sierociuk, Igor Podlubny and Ivo Petras","title":"Experimental evidence of variable-order behavior of ladders and nested\n  ladders","comments":"8 pages, 19 figures, 1 table","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DS math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The experimental study of two kinds of electrical circuits, a domino ladder\nand a nested ladder, is presented. While the domino ladder is known and already\nappeared in the theory of fractional-order systems, the nested ladder circuit\nis presented in this article for the first time. For fitting the measured data,\na new approach is suggested, which is based on using the Mittag-Leffler\nfunction and which means that the data are fitted by a solution of an\ninitial-value problem for a two-term fractional differential equation. The\nexperiment showed that in the frequency domain the domino ladder behaves as a\nsystem of order 0.5 and the nested ladder as a system of order 0.25, which is\nin perfect agreement with the theory developed for their design. In the time\ndomain, however, the order of the domino ladder is changing from roughly 0.5 to\nalmost 1, and the order of the nested ladder is changing in a similar manner,\nfrom roughly 0.25 to almost 1; in both cases, the order 1 is never reached, and\nboth systems remain the systems of non-integer order less than 1. Both studied\ntypes of electrical circuits provide the first known examples of circuits,\nwhich are made of passive elements only and which exhibit in the time domain\nthe behavior of variable order.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 13 Jul 2011 15:21:51 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 14 Jul 2011 12:41:43 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sun, 17 Jul 2011 10:52:05 GMT"}],"update_date":"2011-07-19"}
